Y1  - 1984//
N2  - In 20 anovulatory patients who were normoprolactinaemic, 12 developed transient hyperprolactinaemia when they were treated with human menopausal gonadotropin (hMG) for induction of ovulation. The hyperprolactinaemia was probably due to the increased oestrogen production effect on some susceptible patients. The pregnancy rate was found to be lower in those who developed this condition. The dosage of hMG required was found to be significantly higher in this group. The importance of recognizing this transient hyperprolactinaemia and the probably role of Bromocriptine are discussed. Further study is suggested.
